","text":" in large distributed systems:"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"text"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Systems cannot agree on each message if some systems may fail\n    ↓\nImpossible for all systems to agree consistently\n    ↓\nExactly-once is not fault tolerant in large distributed systems"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"What actually happens"},{"type":"text","text":": Even major platforms like "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Stripe, Kafka, and AWS don't implement exactly-once delivery by default"},{"type":"text","text":" — they rely on "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"at-least-once delivery combined with idempotent operations"},{"type":"text","text":"."}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Exactly-Once Is Actually Idempotent At-Least-Once"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"\"Exactly-once is not considered better because it comes with high cost, whereas at-least-once is good enough\""},{"type":"text","text":":"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"text"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"What you call \"exactly-once\" is actually:\n    ↓\nAt-least-once delivery + Idempotent operations + Deduplication\n    ↓\nSame as at-least-once, but with books kept on duplicates"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Implementation"},{"type":"text","text":": \"By implementing exact-once on top of at-least-once, you will have duplicates (if not exact one) in case of failures and what you need is to de-duplicate\"."}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Comparison Table"}]},{"type":"table","content":[{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableHeader","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Attribute"}]}]},{